Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/Session
Object: A period during which Parliament is able to conduct business on days of its choosing. A session is within a Parliament period. The first session of a Parliament begins on the same day as the Parliament period and ends on a day named in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the Parliament period begin and end on dates named in subsequent prorogation proclamations. The final session of a Parliament ends either with prorogation followed by dissolution or with dissolution. Session periods are the same for both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/ActOfParliament
Object: An Act of Parliament creates, amends or repeals legislation. An Act is a Bill having been passed by Parliament and been given Royal Assent. Acts of Parliament which are in force comprise statute law also known as the statute book.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/DraftBill
Object: A Government Bill issued first in a draft form to allow them to be looked at in detail before they are introduced to Parliament. They are usually examined either by a Commons or Lords select committee or by a specially created joint committee of both Houses of Parliament. This process is known as 'pre-legislative scrutiny'.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/DepartmentalSponsorship
Object: The sponsorship of a bill by a government organisation. Should the machinery of Government change during the passage of a Public Bill, it is possible for the sponsorship of that bill to pass to a different government organisation.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/PublicBill
Object: A proposal for a new law or a proposal to significantly change an existing law affecting the population as a whole. A Public Bill is either a Government Bill or a Private Members' Bill.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/ParliamentActProcedureInvoked
Object: The Parliament Acts of 1911 and 1949 limit the power of the House of Lords in relation to the House of Commons. They replaced the Lords' right to veto Commons Bills with a right only to delay them and put into law the Commons' exclusive powers to pass Bills on public tax and spending. In circumstances where a bill is passed by the House of Commons and rejected by the House of Lords in the same session, it is possible for the Government to introduce a similar bill in the following session. If the House of Commons chooses to invoke the Parliament Act, the House of Lords has one month to agree to the bill, otherwise the Commons may pass the bill unilaterally. The similarity of a bill being introduced in a following session is not made explicit until the Speaker certifies the bill as being subject to the Parliament Act.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/GovernmentOrganisation
Object: Government departments, agencies and public bodies which have responsibility for a specific sector of public administration.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/MemberSponsorship
Object: The sponsorship of a bill by a Member. It is possible for the sponsorship of a bill to pass to a different Member, for example: if a Member is elevated to the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/Incumbency
Object: The holding of a position by a person, including the time period for which this was the case. For example, Philip Hammond holding the position of Foreign Secretary between two dates.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/CarryOver
Object: The act of carrying a bill over from one session to the following session. A bill being carried over results in the creation of a new bill in the new session, the text of the new bill being the text of the original bill as amended in the first session. Public Bills which have not been passed by the end of the session in which they were first introduced will otherwise fall. A bill being before the House of Commons, it is necessary for that House to pass a carry over motion in order for the bill to be carried over into the following session. There is a similar but less formal process in the House of Lords. Private Members' Bills cannot be carried over.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/bill/ExplanatoryNote
Object: Documents explaining the purpose of a Bill. All Government Bills and some Private Members' Bills have accompanying documents.
